Akh'enet is a ruined legal-mortuary relay city between the Southern Oasis and the pyramid approach roads.
It bound oasis water law to pyramid funerary authority. Caravans, bodies, debt, relics, and verdicts all passed through it.
Its oldest creed: "What is unrecorded becomes famine."
The Bellwind Collapse destroyed it: tremor chains ruptured shafts, aquifer backflow carried brine into cisterns, archive vaults flooded.
The city did not die completely. Each district preserves a different political era in ruin.
Factions: Reed Ledger Wardens (water and records first), Moon Sepulchrists (descent rites, militant wing seeks to reopen the Nadir Palace), Salt Jackal Reclaimers (relic brokers and forged-seal traders), Caravan Freeholds (neutral trade hostels).
Key districts: Sunbreak March, Keeper Roadworks, Shuttered Bazaar, Cistern Veins, Necropolis Terraces.
The Nadir Palace was built to reconcile court, water, and death in one ceremonial machine. Its failure is the city's central myth.
Water is testimony: every cistern draw is a legal claim. Death is administrative continuity: contracts survive the person.
Silence is juridical technology: moon-influenced courts used acoustic deprivation for verdicts of unmatched legitimacy.
This is the Khenari homeland. Their diaspora began with the Bellwind Collapse.
